# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: playwright-python
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] A **headless browser** is a web browser without a graphical user interface.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but they are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] They are particularly useful for testing web pages as they are able to render and understand HTML the same way a browser would, including styling elements such as page layout, color, font selection and execution of JavaScript and Ajax which are usually not available when using other testing methods.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Since version 59 of Google Chrome and version 56 of Firefox, there is native support for remote control of the browser.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] This made earlier efforts obsolete, notably PhantomJS.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Headless browsers are also useful for web scraping.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Google stated in 2009 that using a headless browser could help their search engine index content from websites that use Ajax.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] However, a study of browser traffic in 2018 found no preference by malicious actors for headless browsers.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] There is no indication that headless browsers are used more frequently than non-headless browsers for malicious purposes, like DDoS attacks, SQL injections or cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] As several major browsers natively support headless mode through APIs, some software exists to perform browser automation through a unified interface.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Some test automation software and frameworks include headless browsers as part of their testing apparati.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Another approach is to use software that provides browser APIs.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] For example, Deno provides browser APIs as part of its design.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] For Node.js, jsdom is the most complete provider.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] While most are able to support common browser features (HTML parsing, cookies, XHR, some JavaScript, etc.), they do not render the DOM and have limited support for DOM events.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] They usually perform faster than full browsers, but are unable to correctly interpret many popular websites.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] Another is HtmlUnit, a headless browser written in Java.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] HtmlUnit uses the Rhino engine to provide JavaScript and Ajax support as well as partial rendering capability.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] These are various software that provide headless browser APIs.
[src:playwright-python/headless-browser] An earlier effort (2008) was envjs from John Resig, which was a simulated browser environment written in JavaScript for the Rhino engine.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:playwright-python/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:playwright-python/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Playwright was created specifically to accommodate the needs of end-to-end testing.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Playwright supports all modern rendering engines including Chromium, WebKit, and Firefox.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Test on Windows, Linux, and macOS, locally or on CI, headless or headed with native mobile emulation.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] The Playwright library can be used as a general purpose browser automation tool, providing a powerful set of APIs to automate web applications, for both sync and async Python.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] This introduction describes the Playwright Pytest plugin, which is the recommended way to write end-to-end tests.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Playwright recommends using the official Playwright Pytest plugin to write end-to-end tests.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] It provides context isolation, running it on multiple browser configurations out of the box.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Get started by installing Playwright and running the example test to see it in action.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Create a file that follows the `test_` prefix convention, such as `test_example.py`, inside the current working directory or in a sub-directory with the code below.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Make sure your test name also follows the `test_` prefix convention.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] By default tests will be run on chromium.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] This can be configured via the CLI options.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Tests are run in headless mode meaning no browser UI will open up when running the tests.
[src:playwright-python/python-intro] Results of the tests and test logs will be shown in the terminal.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locators are the central piece of Playwright's auto-waiting and retry-ability.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In a nutshell, locators represent a way to find element(s) on the page at any moment.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] These are the recommended built-in locators.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Playwright comes with multiple built-in locators.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] To make tests resilient, we recommend prioritizing user-facing attributes and explicit contracts such as page.get_by_role().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] For example, consider the following DOM structure.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locate the element by its role of `button` with name "Sign in".
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use the code generator to generate a locator, and then edit it as you'd like.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Every time a locator is used for an action, an up-to-date DOM element is located in the page.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In the snippet below, the underlying DOM element will be located twice, once prior to every action.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] This means that if the DOM changes in between the calls due to re-render, the new element corresponding to the locator will be used.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Note that all methods that create a locator, such as page.get_by_label(), are also available on the Locator and FrameLocator classes, so you can chain them and iteratively narrow down your locator.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] The page.get_by_role() locator reflects how users and assistive technology perceive the page, for example whether some element is a button or a checkbox.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] When locating by role, you should usually pass the accessible name as well, so that the locator pinpoints the exact element.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Role locators include buttons, checkboxes, headings, links, lists, tables, and many more and follow W3C specifications for ARIA role, ARIA attributes and accessible name.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Note that many html elements like `<button>` have an implicitly defined role that is recognized by the role locator.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Note that role locators **do not replace** accessibility audits and conformance tests, but rather give early feedback about the ARIA guidelines.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] We recommend prioritizing role locators to locate elements, as it is the closest way to how users and assistive technology perceive the page.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Most form controls usually have dedicated labels that could be conveniently used to interact with the form.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In this case, you can locate the control by its associated label using page.get_by_label().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use this locator when locating form fields.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Inputs may have a placeholder attribute to hint to the user what value should be entered.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can locate such an input using page.get_by_placeholder().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use this locator when locating form elements that do not have labels but do have placeholder texts.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Find an element by the text it contains.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can match by a substring, exact string, or a regular expression when using page.get_by_text().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Matching by text always normalizes whitespace, even with exact match.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] For example, it turns multiple spaces into one, turns line breaks into spaces and ignores leading and trailing whitespace.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] We recommend using text locators to find non interactive elements like `div`, `span`, `p`, etc.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] For interactive elements like `button`, `a`, `input`, etc. use role locators.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can also filter by text which can be useful when trying to find a particular item in a list.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] All images should have an `alt` attribute that describes the image.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can locate an image based on the text alternative using page.get_by_alt_text().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use this locator when your element supports alt text such as `img` and `area` elements.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locate an element with a matching title attribute using page.get_by_title().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use this locator when your element has the `title` attribute.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Testing by test ids is the most resilient way of testing as even if your text or role of the attribute changes, the test will still pass.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] QA's and developers should define explicit test ids and query them with page.get_by_test_id().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] However testing by test ids is not user facing.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] If the role or text value is important to you then consider using user facing locators such as role and text locators.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can also use test ids when you choose to use the test id methodology or when you can't locate by role or text.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] By default, page.get_by_test_id() will locate elements based on the `data-testid` attribute, but you can configure it in your test config or by calling selectors.set_test_id_attribute().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Set the test id to use a custom data attribute for your tests.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In your html you can now use `data-pw` as your test id instead of the default `data-testid`.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] If you absolutely must use CSS or XPath locators, you can use page.locator() to create a locator that takes a selector describing how to find an element in the page.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Playwright supports CSS and XPath selectors, and auto-detects them if you omit `css=` or `xpath=` prefix.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] XPath and CSS selectors can be tied to the DOM structure or implementation.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] These selectors can break when the DOM structure changes.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] CSS and XPath are not recommended as the DOM can often change leading to non resilient tests.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Instead, try to come up with a locator that is close to how the user perceives the page such as role locators or define an explicit testing contract using test ids.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] All locators in Playwright **by default** work with elements in Shadow DOM.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can locate in the same way as if the shadow root was not present at all.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Consider the following DOM structure where we want to click on the buy button of the second product card.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] We have a few options in order to filter the locators to get the right one.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locators can be filtered by text with the locator.filter() method.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] It will search for a particular string somewhere inside the element, possibly in a descendant element, case-insensitively.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locators support an option to only select elements that have or have not a descendant matching another locator.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can therefore filter by any other locator such as a locator.get_by_role(), locator.get_by_test_id(), locator.get_by_text() etc.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] The filtering locator **must be relative** to the original locator and is queried starting with the original locator match, not the document root.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] We can also filter by **not having** a matching element inside.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Note that the inner locator is matched starting from the outer one, not from the document root.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can chain methods that create a locator, like page.get_by_text() or locator.get_by_role(), to narrow down the search to a particular part of the page.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In this example we first create a locator called product by locating its role of `listitem`.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] We can use the product locator again to get by role of button and click it and then use an assertion to make sure there is only one product with the text "Product 2".
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Method locator.and_() narrows down an existing locator by matching an additional locator.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] For example, you can combine page.get_by_role() and page.get_by_title() to match by both role and title.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] If you'd like to target one of the two or more elements, and you don't know which one it will be, use locator.or_() to create a locator that matches any one or both of the alternatives.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] For example, consider a scenario where you'd like to click on a "New email" button, but sometimes a security settings dialog shows up instead.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In this case, you can wait for either a "New email" button, or a dialog and act accordingly.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] If both "New email" button and security dialog appear on screen, the "or" locator will match both of them, possibly throwing the "strict mode violation" error.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] In this case, you can use locator.first to only match one of them.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] It's usually better to find a more reliable way to uniquely identify the element instead of checking the visibility.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Consider a page with two buttons, the first invisible and the second visible.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can assert locators in order to count the items in a list.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use the count assertion to ensure that the list has 3 items.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can assert locators in order to find all the text in a list.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use expect(locator).to_have_text() to ensure that the list has the text "apple", "banana" and "orange".
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] There are many ways to get a specific item in a list.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use the page.get_by_text() method to locate an element in a list by its text content and then click on it.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locate an item by its text content and click it.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use the locator.filter() to locate a specific item in a list.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locate an item by the role of "listitem" and then filter by the text of "orange" and then click it.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Use the page.get_by_test_id() method to locate an element in a list.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You may need to modify the html and add a test id if you don't already have a test id.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Locate an item by its test id of "orange" and then click it.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] If you have a list of identical elements, and the only way to distinguish between them is the order, you can choose a specific element from a list with locator.first, locator.last or locator.nth().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Often times, the page might change, and the locator will point to a completely different element from the one you expected.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Instead, try to come up with a unique locator that will pass the strictness criteria.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] When you have elements with various similarities, you can use the locator.filter() method to select the right one.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can also chain multiple filters to narrow down the selection.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You should now have a "screenshot.png" file in your project's root directory.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] The code inside locator.evaluate_all() runs in the page, you can call any DOM apis there.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] This means that all operations on locators that imply some target DOM element will throw an exception if more than one element matches.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] On the other hand, Playwright understands when you perform a multiple-element operation, so the following call works perfectly fine when the locator resolves to multiple elements.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] You can explicitly opt-out from strictness check by telling Playwright which element to use when multiple elements match, through locator.first, locator.last, and locator.nth().
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] These methods are **not recommended** because when your page changes, Playwright may click on an element you did not intend.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] Instead, follow best practices above to create a locator that uniquely identifies the target element.
[src:playwright-python/python-locators] For less commonly used locators, look at the other locators guide.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:playwright-python/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] A **web browser**, often abbreviated as **browser**, is an application for accessing websites.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] When a user requests a web page from a particular website, the browser retrieves its files from a web server and then displays the page on the user's screen.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Browsers can also display content stored locally on the user's device.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Browsers are used on a range of devices, including desktops, laptops, tablets, smartphones, smartwatches, smart televisions and consoles.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] As of 2026, the most used browsers worldwide are Google Chrome (~69% market share), Safari (~16%), Edge (~5%), Firefox (~2%), Samsung Browser (~2%), and Opera (~2%).
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] As of 2023, an estimated 5.4 billion people had used a browser.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The purpose of a web browser is to fetch content and display it on the user's device.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] This process begins when the user inputs a Uniform Resource Locator (URL), such as *`https://en.wikipedia.org/`*, into the browser's address bar.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Virtually all URLs on the Web start with either *`http:`* or *`https:`* which means they are retrieved with the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] For secure mode (HTTPS), the connection between the browser and web server is encrypted, providing a secure and private data transfer.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] For this reason, a web browser is often referred to as an HTTP client or a user agent.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Requisite materials, including text, style sheets, images, and other types of multimedia, are downloaded from the server.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Once the materials have been downloaded, the web browser's engine (also known as a layout engine or rendering engine) is responsible for converting those resources into an interactive visual representation of the page on the user's device.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Modern web browsers also contain separate JavaScript engines which enable more complex interactive applications inside the browser.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] A web browser that does not render a graphical user interface is known as a headless browser.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Web pages usually contain hyperlinks to other pages and resources.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Each link contains a URL, and when it is clicked or tapped, the browser navigates to the new resource.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Most browsers use an internal cache of web page resources to improve loading times for subsequent visits to the same page.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The cache can store many items, such as large images, so they do not need to be downloaded from the server again.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Cached items are usually only stored for as long as the web server stipulates in its HTTP response messages.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] A web browser is not the same thing as a search engine, though the two are often confused.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] A search engine is a website that provides links to other websites and allows users to search for specific resources using a textual query.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] However, web browsers are often used to access search engines, and most modern browsers allow users to access a default search engine directly by typing a query into the address bar.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The first web browser, called WorldWideWeb, was created in 1990 by Sir Tim Berners-Lee.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] He then recruited Nicola Pellow to write the Line Mode Browser, which displayed web pages on dumb terminals.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The Mosaic web browser was released in April 1993, and was later credited as the first web browser to find mainstream popularity.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Its innovative graphical user interface made the World Wide Web easy to navigate and thus more accessible to the average person.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] This, in turn, sparked the Internet boom of the 1990s, when the Web grew at a very rapid rate.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released the Mosaic-influenced Netscape Navigator in 1994.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Navigator quickly became the most popular browser.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Within a few years, Microsoft gained a dominant position in the browser market for two reasons: it bundled Internet Explorer with its popular Windows operating system and did so as freeware with no restrictions on usage.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The market share of Internet Explorer peaked at over 95% in the early 2000s.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] In 1998, Netscape launched what would become the Mozilla Foundation to create a new browser using the open-source software model.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] This work evolved into the Firefox browser, first released by Mozilla in 2004.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Firefox's market share peaked at 32% in 2010.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Apple released its Safari browser in 2003; it remains the dominant browser on Apple devices, though it did not become popular elsewhere.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, which steadily took market share from Internet Explorer and became the most popular browser in 2012.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Chrome has remained dominant ever since.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] In 2015, Microsoft replaced Internet Explorer with Edge [Legacy] for the Windows 10 release.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] In 2020, this legacy version was replaced by a new Chromium-based version of Edge.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Since the early 2000s, browsers have greatly expanded their HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and multimedia capabilities.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] One reason has been to enable more sophisticated websites, such as web apps.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Another factor is the significant increase of broadband connectivity in many parts of the world, enabling people to access data-intensive content, such as streaming HD video on YouTube, that was not possible during the era of dial-up modems.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Starting in the mid-2020s, browsers with integrated artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities, known as AI browsers, have become increasingly common.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] This includes both new entrants to the browser market, such as Perplexity Comet and ChatGPT Atlas, and established browsers that added AI features, such as Chrome with the Gemini chatbot and Edge with the Copilot chatbot.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The most popular browsers share many features.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] They automatically log users' browsing history, unless the users turn off their browsing history or use the non-logging private mode.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] They also allow users to set bookmarks, customize the browser with extensions, and manage their downloads and passwords.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Some provide a sync service and web accessibility features.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] While mobile browsers have similar UI features as desktop versions, the limitations of the often-smaller touch screens require mobile UIs to be simpler.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The difference is significant for users accustomed to keyboard shortcuts.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Responsive web design is used to create websites that offer a consistent experience across the desktop and mobile versions of the website and across varying screen sizes.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The most popular desktop browsers also have sophisticated web development tools.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Access to some web content — particularly streaming services like Netflix, Disney+, and Spotify — is restricted by Digital Rights Management (DRM) software.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] A web browser is able to access DRM-restricted content through the use of a Content Decryption Module (CDM) such as Widevine.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] As of 2020, the CDMs used by dominant web browsers require browser providers to pay costly license fees, making it unfeasible for most independent open-source browsers to offer access to DRM-restricted content.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Google Chrome has been the dominant browser worldwide since the mid-2010s and currently has a 69% global market share on all devices.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] The other two browsers in the top four are made from different codebases.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Safari, based on Apple's WebKit code, is the second most popular web browser and is dominant on Apple devices, resulting in a 16% global share.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Firefox, in fourth place, with about 2% market share, is based on Mozilla's code.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Both of these codebases are open-source, so a number of small niche browsers are also made from them.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Prior to late 2016, the majority of web traffic came from desktop computers.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] However, since then, mobile devices (smartphones) have represented the majority of web traffic.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] As of February 2025, mobile devices represent a 62% share of Internet traffic, followed by desktop at 36% and tablet at 2%.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Web browsers are popular targets for hackers, who exploit security holes to steal information, destroy files, and partake in other malicious activities.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Browser vendors regularly patch these security holes, so users are strongly encouraged to keep their browser software updated.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Other protection measures are antivirus software and being aware of scams.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] During the course of browsing, cookies received from various websites are stored by the browser.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Some of them contain login credentials or site preferences.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] However, others are used for tracking user behavior over long periods of time, so browsers typically provide a section in the menu for deleting cookies.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Some browsers have more proactive protection against cookies and trackers that limit their functionality and ability to track user behaviour.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Finer-grained management of cookies usually requires a browser extension.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Telemetry data is collected by most popular web browsers, which can usually be opted out of by the user.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] A study from 2020 portrays that there are two tiers of browsers in terms of privacy: the privacy-focused ones (Brave, DuckDuckGo, LibreWolf, Tor,Mullvad, Helium and Firefox-Focus) perform better than popular ones (Chrome, Firefox, and Safari) and recommend the first ones.
[src:playwright-python/web-browser] Blocking fingerprinting, cookies, tracking scripts, ads, etc. seems to explain that difference.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium was originally developed by Jason Huggins in 2004 as an internal tool at ThoughtWorks.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Huggins was later joined by other programmers and testers at ThoughtWorks, before Paul Hammant joined the team and steered the development of the second mode of operation that would later become "Selenium Remote Control" (RC).
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] In 2005 Dan Fabulich and Nelson Sproul (with help from Pat Lightbody) made an offer to accept a series of patches that would transform Selenium-RC into what it became best known for.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] In the same meeting, the steering of Selenium as a project would continue as a committee, with Huggins and Hammant being the ThoughtWorks representatives.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Together with others like Jennifer Bevan, he continued with the development and stabilization of Selenium RC.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] At the same time, Simon Stewart at ThoughtWorks developed a superior browser automation tool called WebDriver.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] In 2009, after a meeting between the developers at the Google Test Automation Conference, it was decided to merge the two projects, and call the new project Selenium WebDriver, or Selenium 2.0.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] In 2008, Philippe Hanrigou (then at ThoughtWorks) made "Selenium Grid", which provides a hub allowing the running of multiple Selenium tests concurrently on any number of local or remote systems, thus minimizing test execution time.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Grid offered, as open source, a similar capability to the internal/private Google cloud for Selenium RC.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Pat Lightbody had already made a private cloud for "HostedQA" which he went on to sell to Gomez, Inc.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The name Selenium comes from a joke made by Huggins in an email, mocking a competitor named Mercury, saying that mercury poisoning can be cured by taking supplements of the element selenium.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The others that received the email took the name and ran with it.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium is composed of several components with each taking on a specific role in aiding the development of web application test automation.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium IDE is a complete integrated development environment (IDE) for Selenium tests.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] It is implemented as a Firefox Add-On and as a Chrome Extension.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] It allows for recording, editing and debugging of functional tests.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] It was previously known as Selenium Recorder.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium-IDE was originally created by Shinya Kasatani and donated to the Selenium project in 2006.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium IDE began being actively maintained in 2018.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Scripts may be automatically recorded and edited manually providing autocompletion support and the ability to move commands around quickly.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Scripts are recorded in *Selenese*, a special test scripting language for Selenium.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenese provides commands for performing actions in a browser (click a link, select an option) and for retrieving data from the resulting pages.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenese serves as the language for composing Selenium Commands, which are utilized in the testing of web applications.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] These commands, tailored to the HTML tags of UI elements, facilitate the verification of their existence.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] They guide Selenium in comprehending the specific actions or operations to execute.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] As an alternative to writing tests in Selenese, tests can also be written in various programming languages.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] These tests then communicate with Selenium by calling methods in the Selenium Client API.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium currently provides client APIs for Java, C#, Ruby, JavaScript, R and Python.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium Remote Control (RC) is a server, written in Java, that accepts commands for the browser via HTTP.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] RC makes it possible to write automated tests for a web application in any programming language, which allows for better integration of Selenium in existing unit test frameworks.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] To make writing tests easier, Selenium project currently provides client drivers for PHP, Python, Ruby, .NET, Perl and Java.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The Java driver can also be used with JavaScript (via the Rhino engine).
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] An instance of selenium RC server is needed to launch html test case - which means that the port should be different for each parallel run.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] However, for Java/PHP test case only one Selenium RC instance needs to be running continuously.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium Remote Control was a refactoring of Driven Selenium or Selenium B designed by Paul Hammant, credited with Jason as co-creator of Selenium.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The original version directly launched a process for the browser in question, from the test language of Java, .NET, Python or Ruby.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The wire protocol (called 'Selenese' in its day) was reimplemented in each language port.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] After the refactor by Dan Fabulich and Nelson Sproul (with help from Pat Lightbody) there was an intermediate daemon process between the driving test script and the browser.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The benefits included the ability to drive remote browsers and the reduced need to port every line of code to an increasingly growing set of languages.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] *Selenium Remote Control* completely took over from the Driven Selenium code-line in 2006.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The browser pattern for 'Driven'/'B' and 'RC' was response/request, which subsequently became known as Comet.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium RC served as the flagship testing framework of the entire project of selenium for a long-standing time.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium RC is the first and foremost automated web testing tool that enabled users to adopt their preferred programming language.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] With the release of Selenium 2, Selenium RC has been officially deprecated in favor of Selenium WebDriver.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] At the core of Selenium is Selenium WebDriver, an interface to write instructions that work interchangeably across browsers.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium WebDriver accepts commands (sent in Selenese, or via a Client API) and sends them to a browser.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] This is implemented through a browser-specific browser driver, which sends commands to a browser and retrieves results.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Most browser drivers actually launch and access a browser application (such as Firefox, Google Chrome, Internet Explorer, Safari, or Microsoft Edge); there is also an HtmlUnit browser driver, which simulates a browser using the headless browser HtmlUnit.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Since Selenium 4 and Google Chrome version 109, headless mode has been supported through a native implementation of the browser, in which Chrome operates without a graphical user interface but with rendering and execution behavior identical to the regular mode.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Unlike in Selenium 1, where the Selenium server was necessary to run tests, Selenium WebDriver does not need a special server to execute tests.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Instead, the WebDriver directly starts a browser instance and controls it.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] However, Selenium Grid can be used with WebDriver to execute tests on remote systems (see below).
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Where possible, WebDriver uses native operating system level functionality rather than browser-based JavaScript commands to drive the browser.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] This bypasses problems with subtle differences between native and JavaScript commands, including security restrictions.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] As of early 2012, Simon Stewart (inventor of WebDriver), who was then with Google, and David Burns of Mozilla were negotiating with the W3C to make WebDriver an Internet standard.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] In July 2012, the working draft was released and the recommendation followed in June 2018.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium WebDriver (Selenium 2.0) is fully implemented and supported in JavaScript (Node.js), Python, Ruby, Java, Kotlin, and C#.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] As of 2021, Selenium 4 is a release candidate.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium Grid is a server that allows tests to use web browser instances running on remote machines.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] With Selenium Grid, one server acts as the central hub.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Tests contact the hub to obtain access to browser instances.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The hub has a list of servers that provide access to browser instances (WebDriver nodes), and lets tests use these instances.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] Selenium Grid allows running tests in parallel on multiple machines and to manage different browser versions and browser configurations centrally (instead of in each individual test).
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The ability to run tests on remote browser instances is useful to spread the load of testing across several machines and to run tests in browsers running on different platforms or operating systems.
[src:playwright-python/webdriver] The latter is particularly useful in cases where not all browsers to be used for testing can run on the same platform.
